{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511381"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:42:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:42:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11747"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11747"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.17,0.1,0,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109002"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4360"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91372"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6021"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109002"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to his general practitioner seeking advice on his \u0027heartburn.\u0027 He describe a three year history of burning chest pain, which starts in his epigastrium and radiates upwards. This is accompanied with regurgitation and metallic taste in mouth.  The episodes happen two or three times week and he takes an antacid preparation to relieve his symptoms. He smokes 15 cigarettes a day, enjoys a couple of glasses of wine in the evening, and eat take-out meals about four times a week. The physical examination is unremarkable, apart from his BMI of 33.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the regular use of a proton pump inhibitor, his doctor provides some advice on potential long-term strategies to minimise his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be effective in reducing his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smoking cessation","Reduce alcohol consumption","Dietary change","Regular exercise","Weight reduction"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) is a common condition that affects 10-20% population of the western world. Typical presentation of GORD includes burning central chest pain accompanied with a metallic taste in mouth. Some patients will also experience nausea and dry-cough. Although proton-pump inhibitor has been proven to effectively manage symptoms of GORD, clinicians should not miss the importance of lifestyle modifications in the long term management of GORD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeight loss\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant non-pharmacological management of GORD. Obesity is heavily associated with reflux disease, and research has shown that weight loss has a dose-dependent effect on the reduction of symptoms; 3.5kg/m2 reduction in weight can reduce frequency of symptoms by about 40%. Therefore weight management is a critically important lifestyle modification in the long-term management of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStopping smoking and reducing alcohol consumption is highly beneficial for the patient\u0027s overall health, but smoking has not been proven to have any effect on improving symptoms of GORD. Alcohol can impair oesophageal motility, affect lower oesophageal sphincter function and increase gastric acid secretion. Whilst this particular patient might be considered using alcohol to excess, reducing its consumption will not be as effective as losing weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERaising the head of the bed (with a brick under the top legs of the bed) can help moderate symptoms, as will eating the evening meal well before bedtime. Smaller meal sizes should be encouraged. Whilst regular exercise and eating a healthy and varied diet will also play a part in reducing his reflux symptoms, their place will be strategies to help the patient reduce his weight - the weight loss being the key factor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Weight loss is the most effective lifestyle modification in reducing symptoms of gastro-oesophageal-reflux disease."],"references":["Keung C, Hebbard G. The management of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Australian prescriber. 2016 Feb;39(1):6. Available via: https://www.nps.org.au/australian-prescriber/articles/the-management-of-gastro-oesophageal-reflux-disease#r3","Miller G, Wong C, Pollack A. Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) in Australian general practice patients. Australian family physician. 2015 Oct;44(10):701-4. Available via: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/october/gastro-oesophageal-reflux-disease-gord-in-australi","Kaltenbach T, Crockett S, Gerson LB. Are Lifestyle Measures Effective in Patients With Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease? An Evidence-Based Approach. Arch Intern Med. 2006;166(9):965-971.","Keung C, Hebbard G. The management of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Australian Prescriber [Internet]. 2016 Feb 1;39(1):6\u201310. Available from: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/the-management-of-gastro-oesophageal-reflux-disease.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91372"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11747"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91372"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T01:02:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T01:02:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4360"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109002"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"351","links":{"self":"https://app